<article>
    <h1>NYSE scraps plans to delist 3 Chi&#xAD;nese tele&#xAD;com gi&#xAD;ants</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210106/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-06"><time>2021-01-06</time></a>
        - <span>BUSINESS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>• The New York Stock Ex­change (NYSE) has said it will no longer delist China’s three big­gest state-owned telecom­mu­ni­ca­tions com­pa­nies, back­track­ing on a plan that had threat­ened to es­ca­late tensions be­tween the world’s two largest economies.</p>
    <p>NYSE’s U-turn came just four days af­ter the ex­change said it would re­move shares of China Mo­bile, China Tele­com and China Uni­com Hong Kong to com­ply with a US ex­ec­u­tive or­der.</p>
    <p>The bourse cited “con­sul­ta­tion with rel­e­vant reg­u­la­tory au­thor­i­ties” in a brief state­ment late on Mon­day an­nounc­ing the re­ver­sal.</p>
    <p>Shares of the three com­pa­nies ral­lied on the lat­est devel­op­ment, ris­ing more than 6 per cent in Hong Kong trad­ing.</p>
    <p>On New Year’s Eve, NYSE said it would delist the com­pa­nies to com­ply with a Novem­ber or­der by Pres­i­dent Don­ald Trump bar­ring Amer­i­can in­vest­ments in Chi­nese firms owned or con­trolled by the mil­i­tary.</p>
    <p>It was the first time an Amer­i­can ex­change had an­nounced plans to re­move a Chi­nese com­pany as a di­rect re­sult of ris­ing geopo­lit­i­cal tensions be­tween the two su­per­pow­ers.</p>
    <p>The move to delist the shares had height­ened con­cerns about tit-for-tat sanc­tions on Chi­nese and Amer­i­can com­pa­nies.</p>
    <p>The for­mer have turned to the US mar­kets for cap­i­tal and global pres­tige for over two decades, rais­ing at least US$144 billion (S$190 billion) from some of the world’s largest in­vestors.</p>
    <p>Wall Street banks are par­tic­u­larly keen to see a ratch­et­ing down of tensions af­ter gain­ing un­prece­dented scope to op­er­ate in China last year.</p>


